[[Matthew McConaughey]] is an American actor and producer who rose to prominence with his role in the 1993 ensemble comedy film ''[[Dazed and Confused (film)|Dazed and Confused]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dockterman|first1=Eliana|title=Charting the McConaissance: The Evolution of Matthew McConaughey|url=http://time.com/12701/charting-the-mcconaissance-the-evolution-of-matthew-mcconaughey/|accessdate=May 8, 2018|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=February 25, 2014}}</ref> The film was well received by critics.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/dazed-and-confused | title=Dazed and Confused reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]]  | accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Since then, McConaughey has received various awards and nominations, including an [[Academy Award]], a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], two Critics' Choice Awards, a [[MTV Movie Award]] and a [[People’s Choice Award]]. He has also been nominated for five [[Teen Choice Awards]] and two [[Primetime Emmy Awards|Emmys]].

Three years after his role in ''Dazed and Confused'', in 1996, McConaughey played the lead role of a lawyer in the movie ''[[A Time to Kill (1996 film)|A Time to Kill]]'', for which he won the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]]. His next appearances—in the science fiction drama ''[[Contact (1997 American film)|Contact]]'' (1997), alongside [[Jodie Foster]], and the war film ''[[U-571 (film)|U-571]]'' (2000)—garnered him two [[Blockbuster Entertainment Award]] nominations. In the early 2000s, he starred in multiple romantic comedies, including ''[[The Wedding Planner]]'' (2001) and ''[[How to Lose a Guy in 10 Days]]'' (2003), for which he received four Teen Choice Award nominations. He received two more nominations and the People's Choice Award for Favorite Male Action Star for his role in the 2005 action-comedy film ''[[Sahara (2005 film)|Sahara]]''.

McConaughey received the [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his role in ''[[Bernie (2011 film)|Bernie]]'' (2011) and ''[[Magic Mike]]'' (2012) and was also awarded the [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Supporting Actor|Critics' Choice Movie Award in the same category]] for the latter. He played the role of a hit man in the black comedy crime film ''[[Killer Joe (film)|Killer Joe]]'' (2011) for which he was awarded the [[Saturn Award for Best Actor]]. In the same year, McConaughey starred in ''[[Mud (2012 film)|Mud]]'' (2012), which earned him the [[Independent Spirit Robert Altman Award]]. The following year, McConaughey played lead role of [[Ron Woodroof]], a real life AIDS patient in the 1980s, in the biopic drama ''[[Dallas Buyers Club]]'' to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/dallas-buyers-club | title=Dallas Buyers Club reviews |publisher=Metacritic  | accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> He won the [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Critics' Choice Movie Award]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor – Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]] for his role in the film. In 2014, he starred in the epic sci-fi ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' for which he received a Saturn Award for Best Actor nomination. In November of the same year, he was inducted to the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Walk of Fame: Matthew McConaughey|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/matthew-mcconaughey|publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref>  McConaughey co-produced and acted in the crime anthology television series ''[[True Detective]]'', which earned him [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actor in a Drama Series|Critics' Choice Television Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor – Miniseries or Television Film|Golden Globe]] nomination. He also received two Primetime Emmy nominations, one for his [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|role as an actor]] and other for his [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|role as an executive producer]], and a [[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Episodic Drama|Producers Guild of America Award]] nomination. For his roles in the war film ''[[Free State of Jones (film)|Free State of Jones]]'' and ''[[Gold (2016 film)|Gold]]'' (both 2016), he was nominated for the [[Women Film Critics Circle]] Award for Best Actor and the Saturn Award for Best Actor, respectively.

